{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17477747","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17477747"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:04:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:04:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14711"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14711","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14711"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.64,0.28,0.02,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7404"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58126"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7404","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7404"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14711"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43585"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"1899"},{"type":"tags","id":"2210"},{"type":"tags","id":"4668"},{"type":"tags","id":"4836"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18077"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37614"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58126","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58126"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA six-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his parent with a three-month history of soiling his underwear. He has recently started school and his teacher has expressed concerns. His parent reports that he passes small amounts of loose stool two to three times per day, but also occasionally passes large, hard stools every seven to ten days. He has been refusing to use the school toilets. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His development has been normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His abdomen is soft but distended, with a palpable firm mass in the left lower quadrant. Perianal examination reveals no fissures or skin tags. Neurological examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Coeliac disease","Constipation with overflow","Functional faecal incontinence","Inflammatory bowel disease","Hirschsprung disease"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child presents with the classic features of \u003Cstrong\u003Econstipation with overflow\u003C/strong\u003E. The combination of intermittent large, hard stools with frequent small amounts of loose stool suggests overflow incontinence. The palpable abdominal mass and history of toilet avoidance are supporting features. This is a common problem in school-aged children, often precipitated by withholding behaviour.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFunctional faecal incontinence\u003C/strong\u003E without constipation is less common and would not typically present with a palpable abdominal mass or history of large, hard stools. These children usually have normal bowel habits between episodes of incontinence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHirschsprung disease\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents in the newborn period with delayed passage of meconium and subsequent constipation. Late presentation is rare and would typically have a lifelong history of symptoms rather than recent onset.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInflammatory bowel disease\u003C/strong\u003E would typically present with other symptoms such as weight loss, growth failure, abdominal pain, and blood in the stool. The intermittent passage of large, hard stools would be unusual.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoeliac disease\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with diarrhoea, failure to thrive, and other features of malabsorption. While it can cause changes in bowel habits, the pattern described here is much more consistent with constipation with overflow.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of constipation with overflow includes education about the condition, disimpaction if needed, maintenance laxative therapy, and behavioural strategies to establish regular toileting habits. It is important to address any underlying anxiety about toilet use at school.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Faecal incontinence in children is commonly due to overflow from chronic constipation rather than true incontinence.","A thorough history should include bowel habits, diet, and any withholding behaviours.","Physical examination should assess for an abdominal faecal mass and perform a brief neurological examination."],"references":["Constipation in children and young people: diagnosis and management. London: National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE); 2017 Jul. (NICE Clinical Guidelines, No. 99.) Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK554924/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43585"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14711"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43585","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43585"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-29T13:59:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-29T14:00:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7404"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58126"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji